1 // *****************************************************************************
2 /*!
3  \file src/Control/Keywords.h
4  \author J. Bakosi
5  \copyright 2012-2015, Jozsef Bakosi, 2016, Los Alamos National Security, LLC.
6  \brief Definition of all keywords
7  \details This file contains the definition of all keywords, including those
8  of command-line argument parsers as well as input, i.e., control, file
9  parsers. All keywords are shared among all parsers of all executables.
10 
11  All keywords are case-sensitive.
12 
13  The information contained in this file is used to build data structures for
14  on-screen help on the command-line arguments and control file keywords,
15  available via the --help, --helpctr, and --helpkw command-line arguments.
16 
17  A note on design: Defining structs that have static member functions
18  returning a std::string is a way of storing C++-style strings at
19  compile-time (which is not possible in a straightforward manner at this
20  time). This could also be done with C-style const char* as well. The
21  '*_info' structs store these strings, which then is used to specialize the
22  _kw::keyword_ template, defined in Control/Keyword.h. Specializing the
23  _keyword_ template also requires a specification of the precise string of
24  characters that make up a keyword eventually matched by the parsers. Since
25  these are all template arguments, the construction of keywords, their help,
26  as well as all grammars, are entirely assembled at compile-time. Since the
27  '*_info' struct member functions are static, they can be called without
28  instantiating an object and thus available at compile-time.
29 
30  The definition of an '*_info' struct _requires_ at least the name, short,
31  and long descriptions, defined by member functions _name()_,
32  _shortDescription()_, and _longDescription()_, respectively. Everything else
33  is optional. However, when adding a new keyword it is highly recommended to
34  define all of the _optional_ members if they make sense for the given
35  keyword. If an expect value type is also given, that can be hooked up into
36  where it is used.
37 
38  The most general definition of a keyword is as follows:
39 
40  \code{.cpp}
41  // Keyword info definition
42  struct keyword_info {
43 
44  // Required very short name, usually a single word or (for e.g.
45  // policies) a single character. This can be the keyword itself, but
46  // does not have to be. This field is used as an id of the option or
47  // setting.
48  static std::string name() { return "Name"; }
49 
50  // Required short keyword description
51  static std::string shortDescription() { return "Short description"; }
52 
53  // Required detailed keyword description. This returns a string literal,
54  // since this is usually multi-line and it is less work to maintain this
55  // way.
56  static std::string longDescription() { return
57  R"(Longer, possibly multi-line description of the keyword. Example
58  usage of the keyword is welcome here. Don't worry about formatting:
59  when this field is printed, extra spaces will be removed and line
60  breaks will be inserted.)";
61  }
62 
63  // Optional keyword alias. See also kw::Alias and
64  // <tpl_install_dir>/include/pegtl/pegtl/constants.hh for examples
65  // of what can be passed as template arguments (basically single
66  // characters). The one below defines the character 'c' as the alias.
67  // Aliases are single character long. The idea of an alias is to have a
68  // long as well as a short keyword for the same functionality.
69  // Currently, this is only hooked up for command-line arguments and not
70  // for control-file keywords, which is intentional. Command-line
71  // arguments are a lot less than control file keywords and are more
72  // frequently typed by the user. Thus command-line argument aliases are
73  // user-friendly. There are many control file keywords and aliases would
74  // only cause confusion. Defining an alias for a command-line argument
75  // enables the command-line parser to match on '--longer_keyword' as
76  // well as on '-c'. Depending on whether the alias typedef is defined
77  // for a keyword or not, the correct grammar is automatically generated
78  // at compile-time, matching on both the longer keyword as well as on
79  // the alias. Defining an alias for a control file keyword can be done
80  // but has no effect in a control file parser.
81  using alias = Alias< c >;
82 
83  // Optional single-character (policy) code. See also kw::Code and
84  // <tpl_install_dir/include/pegtl/pegtl/constants.hh for examples
85  // of what can be passed as template arguments (basically single
86  // characters). The one below defines the character 'C' as the (policy)
87  // code. This code is used for abbreviating policies used to configure
88  // various orthogonal behaviors of classes using policy-based design.
89  using code = Code< C >;
90 
91  // Optional expected data for the keyword - bundled to struct expect.
92  // This struct is entirely optional within a keyword definition.
93  // However, if it is defined, it must at least define the static member
94  // function description() which returns the description of the type the
95  // keyword expects. It may also optionally define the following fields:
96  //
97  // - type - defining the expected type
98  // - lower - lower bound of the expected value
99  // - upper - upper bound of the expected value
100  // - choices - valid choices for the expected value
101  //
102  struct expect {
103 
104  // If this struct is defined, required expected type description, max
105  // 10 characters long
106  static std::string description() { return "int"; }
107 
108  // Optional expected type
109  using type = std::streamsize;
110 
111  // Optional expected value lower bound
112  static const type lower = 1;
113 
114  // Optional expected value upper bound
115  static const type upper = std::numeric_limits< tk::real >::digits10 + 1;
116 
117  // Optional expected valid choices description, here giving
118  // information on the expected type and the valid bounds. Note that
119  // this can be any string, but if they exist, it is a good idea give
120  // at least some information on the bounds, as below, since the bounds
121  // are NOT displayed in the help for a keyword. This decision keeps
122  // the bounds specifications generic since they can be any type. As a
123  // result, the help structures, defined in HelpFactory.h, are simpler
124  // as they do not have to be parameterized by the type of the bounds,
125  // which greatly simplifies that code.
126  static std::string choices() {
127  return "integer [" + std::to_string(lower) + "..." +
128  std::to_string(upper) + ']';
129  }
130 
131  };
132 
133  };
134 
135  // Keyword definition, passing the above info struct as the first
136  // template argument, and the rest of the template arguments are the
137  // characters of the keyword to be matched by the parser. Remember: all
138  // keywords are case-sensitive. This one contrived example below defines
139  // keyword 'kw', matching the keyword 'KeYwOrD'.
140  using kw = keyword< keyword_info, K,e,Y,w,O,r,D >;
141  \endcode
142  \see Control/Keyword.h
143  \see Control/HelpFactory.h
144 */

2195  defined as usual: x = X - <X>, and b' and kappa' are user-specified
2196  constants. Similar to the number-fraction beta SDE, there two additional
2197  random variables computed besides, X, and they are rho(X) and V(X). For more
2198  detail on the number-fraction beta SDE, see the help on keyword
2199  'numfracbeta'. For more details on the beta SDE, see
